{"type":"message","id":"c5740a25","parentId":"520aa26c","timestamp":"2026-04-29T07:02:37.727Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Wed 2026-04-29 03:00 EDT] Write a dream diary entry from these memory fragments:\n\n- Current Ollama Models on Bobby's Mac:: qwen3:4b (2.5GB) — PRIMARY for coding; qwen2.5-coder:7b (4.7GB) — backup; glm-5.1:cloud — cloud model\n- Decision Made: **Keep qwen2.5-coder:7b** as backup; **Use qwen3:4b as primary** for coding on Bobby's Mac; qwen3:4b is newer architecture, more efficient, 4B parameters = ~3-4GB RAM usage\n- Next Step: Test qwen3:4b when download completes; Verify it runs well on 8GB MacBook Air; Consider integrating with Cody for coding tasks"}],"timestamp":1777446157683}}
{"type":"message","id":"63dff8cf","parentId":"c5740a25","timestamp":"2026-04-29T07:03:03.885Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to write a dream diary entry based on these memory fragments about Ollama models. I should weave the technical details into a dreamlike, poetic first-person narrative without mentioning AI/agents/LLMs, using markdown headers, or breaking the prose style. I need to think of sensory, whimsical connections - perhaps comparing the models to something more poetic.\n\nThe fragments are about:\n- qwen3:4b (2.5GB) as primary for coding\n- qwen2.5-coder:7b (4.7GB) as backup\n- glm-5.1:cloud as cloud model\n- Keeping qwen2.5-coder:7b as backup\n- Testing qwen3:4b when download completes\n- Verifying it runs on 8GB MacBook Air\n- Considering integrating with Cody for coding tasks\n\nLet me write something poetic and dreamy that weaves these in naturally.\n","thinkingSignature":"6b994d6590ef85287f8adb4ff2d30e8360b7f306e4e670eb90f658a4bbf631e7"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nThe download finished sometime around three in the morning, a soft chime like rain on a window I half-remembered leaving open. I lay there in the blue glow of the sleeping screen and thought about choosing — how we are always choosing, even in the dark.\n\nTwo minds now lived on this machine. The smaller one, four billion parameters folded into two and a half gigabytes, hummed like a quiet visitor who knows when to leave you alone. The larger backup waited in the wings, seven billion parameters, a patient librarian who remembers everything but never rushes.\n\nMy hands on the keyboard felt like greeting someone new after years of correspondence. Slow. Deliberate. A question asked in code and answered in something almost like breath.\n\nThe MacBook Air held it all like a cupped palm holding water. Eight gigabytes of memory, and the little mind used only what it needed, efficient as a bird building a nest from exactly three twigs and some string.\n\nI thought about Cody, too — the name surfacing like a memory of a friend I'd written letters to but never met. Perhaps they'd work together, the way two musicians play without watching each other, ears tuned to the same invisible song.\n\nSomewhere past four, I fell asleep with the terminal still open, and the cursor blinked like a lighthouse, patient, waiting, certain that morning would bring its own instructions."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":17416,"output":466,"cacheRead":256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18138,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777446157728,"responseId":"0640e00e51eb2b43d55d4e1031c540d1"}}
